##  Beagle use

Beagle's basic verb vocabulary is HTTP-like and all addressing is URI-based.

  - `get <uri>` is clone/pull/checkout;
  - `post <uri>` is commit/fast-forward/push;
  - `patch <uri>` is merge/rebase/cherry-pick;
  - `put <file>` is stage (also set ref);
  - `delete <file>` is stage deletion (also drop ref);

Most of the time you would probably use the TUI.
Start with `be status` or `be work` for an overview.
All Beagle commands start the pager/TUI by default.
`:` is the command mode (e.g. `:status<Enter>`).
`q` or `:quit<Enter>` is quit.

##  Beagle features

 1. This implementation is [TUI-centric][s], any command opens a pager.
 2. The TUI is browser-like, all things that can be clickable are clickable.
 3. Both external (e.g. GitHub) and internal (e.g. worktrees) addressing is URI-based.
 4. Beagle expects [*lots* of worktrees][w] and many agentic sessions to run in parallel.
 5. Worktrees in turn get organized into a tree-of-life through upstream-fork links.
    That is essential to keep track of them and propagate the changes.

##  Build and Installation

The only dependency is [JAB][j] the anti-bloat JavaScript runtime.
JAB packs a lot of revision-control-specific bindings and APIs.

 1. Build JAB (cmake) or [download][r] it from GitHub, install it in your `$PATH`. 
 2. You may also want to install a symlink, like `be -> jab` to use the `be` command.
 3. Clone the Beagle repo [itself][i].
 4. JAB picks the sources from `jsrc/` dirs in `$PWD` and up the parent chain (not `node_modules`).
    See the `jsrc` self-link in this repo; it lets Beagle revision-control itself.
 5. `cd beagle-ext`
 6. `be status`
 7. You may submodule beagle-ext into your project as `jsrc/` or make `$HOME/jsrc` symlink.

##  Customization and Speciation

Any user-facing behavior is implemented in JavaScript and customizable.
Users are expected to develop their custom verb/view sets. 
Any established workflow should be taken from the LLM's probabilistic hands and [automated][a].
Just put your `jsrc/` on a different level than Beagle's if you want to build on top of it.
Creating your own set of commands from scratch is also OK, it just takes longer.
All the revision-control heavy-lifting, source code tokenization and suchlike is all done by [libdog][d] through JAB bindings.

##  Contribution

Beagle is very experimental. All contributions and (especially) feedback are appreciated.

